[111.865403, "o", "ait to block and harvest the result this turn since the docs fetch should complete \u001b[0m\u001b[24;1H\u001b[2K         \u001b[2msoon.\u001b[0m\u001b[25;1H\u001b[2K  \u001b[36m→\u001b[0m \u001b[1;36mtask$wait\u001b[0m({\"task-id\" \"task-764\", \"timeout-ms\" 60000}): called \u001b[2m→\u001b[0m \u001b[92mdone\u001b[0m, 7.3s, 1.9k chars\u001b[26;1H\u001b[2K\u001b[2m[\u001b[0m\u001b[1;96m+\u001b[0m\u001b[2m] \u001b[0m\u001b[1;97mIteration 3 / 100\u001b[0m  \u001b[2m(31455 tok)\u001b[0m  \u001b[2m(9.1s)\u001b[0m\u001b[27;1H\u001b[2K\u001b[2m  Think: \u001b[0m\u001b[2mThe skill$find-docs call (task-764) completed in iteration 2 via task$wait, and the async completion \u001b[0m\u001b[28;1H\u001b[2K         \u001b[2mwas harvested in iteration 3. I have the full documentation answer. No further tool calls are needed \u001b[0m\u001b[29;1H\u001b[2K         \u001b[2m— I'll summarize the React useState hook covering its signature, return value, and a tiny example.\u001b[0m"]
